  &lt;h1 class=&quot;top&quot;&gt;A Scene at the Sea [Takeshi Kitano 1991]&lt;/h1&gt;  &lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Movie title:&lt;/strong&gt; A Scene at the Sea (Ano natsu, ichiban shizukana umi)&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Director:&lt;/strong&gt; Takeshi Kitano&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Genre:&lt;/strong&gt; Drama&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Year:&lt;/strong&gt; 1991&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rating:&lt;/strong&gt; 7.4/10 (527 votes)&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;IMDB link:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://imdb.com/title/tt0103704/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;http://imdb.com/title/tt0103704/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;  &lt;/ul&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plot:&lt;/strong&gt; A deaf garbage collector happens upon a discarded and broken surfboard. The discovery plants in him dreams of becoming a surf champion. Encouraged by his also deaf girlfriend, he persists against all odds.&lt;br /&gt;
Though trapped in silence, their expression of love is no less profound. A heartrending masterpiece that, as with Kitano's other films Sonatine and Fireworks, has a sharp eye for human frailties and a love for the courage of the underdog.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;h1&gt;Cover&lt;/h1&gt;
